 {"id":"bd-j9jo3.1.12","title":"robot-redesign/contracts: define watch, subscription, heartbeat, and event-taxonomy semantics","description":"Define the long-lived watch and streaming contract for ntm so agents can safely consume ongoing event flows instead of treating them like one-shot JSON responses. This task exists because `vibe_cockpit` gets an important operator-facing detail right: liveness, event classes, and narrow subscriptions are first-class semantics, not transport accidents. Our redesign already covers replay, cursors, boundedness, and recovery, but it still does not explicitly define how a consumer should interpret quiet periods, heartbeats, filtered streams, or source-progress events.","design":"The contract should define a stable watch-event taxonomy for ntm's operator loop, including which classes are material durable events versus ephemeral keepalives or progress annotations, how event severity and reason-code semantics relate to attention and incidents, and how consumers subscribe narrowly without text matching. It should specify heartbeat or keepalive semantics, idle-vs-stuck interpretation, replay-to-live handoff markers, filter and subscription selectors such as event class, severity, source, session, agent, incident, or other stable references, and what happens when a selector is unsupported, too broad, stale, or produces bounded or backpressured output.

It should also define how source-progress or collector-status style signals appear without turning ntm into a generic telemetry firehose, how watch semantics reuse the stable identity, explainability, request-correlation, and boundedness contracts already being defined elsewhere, and how these rules remain aligned across CLI, REST, SSE, and WebSocket variants. The goal is not to build a pubsub framework for its own sake. The goal is to make long-lived robot consumption trustworthy: consumers should know whether a stream is alive, what kind of thing just happened, why nothing is happening, and how to subscribe to the slice they actually need.","acceptance_criteria":"Produce a self-contained watch and streaming contract that downstream attention, parity, diagnostics, registry, docs, and validation work can implement directly.

The result must make it obvious how consumers interpret event classes, heartbeats, quiet periods, replay-to-live transitions, filtered subscriptions, backpressure or boundedness behavior, and source-progress annotations without inferring semantics from incidental formatter behavior.","notes":"A stream that cannot tell the difference between healthy idle, selective filtering, and silent failure is not agent-ergonomic. This bead exists to prevent that ambiguity from being normalized into the product.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":180,"created_at":"2026-03-22T00:46:38.677072781Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-22T00:47:55.669391028Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["contracts","robot-redesign","streaming"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.12","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:46:38.677072781Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.12","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.10","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:47:51.895860203Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.12","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.11","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:47:51.118693943Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.12","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.4","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:47:55.668508175Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.12","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:47:54.933808210Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.12","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.7","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:47:54.198870200Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.12","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.8","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:47:53.415276535Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.12","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.9","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:47:52.647006823Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"bd-j9jo3.1.13","title":"robot-redesign/contracts: define bounded as-of inspection and incident-replay semantics","description":"Define how ntm supports bounded historical inspection so operators and agents can answer questions like what did ntm believe when this incident opened or what did this section look like at a recent timestamp without manually replaying raw events. This task exists because `vibe_cockpit` treats incident replay and point-in-time reconstruction as a first-class debugging affordance, and our redesign still lacks an explicit contract for that capability.","design":"The contract should define a narrow, operator-focused form of historical inspection rather than a broad analytics feature. It should specify how incident-centric replay and bounded as-of reconstruction work, what recent time windows are supported, how replay targets are referenced, whether a response is reconstructed on demand or served from a cached snapshot, how partial or unavailable source history is reported, and how replay semantics relate to stable identities, diagnostics handles, evidence, boundedness, and request-correlation rules.

It should also define how consumers ask for recent historical context without confusing it with live snapshot or raw event replay, how replay or as-of responses advertise staleness and confidence, and how post-mortem export or sharing behaves if that is exposed later. The goal is not to turn ntm into a historical warehouse. The goal is to make recent operational debugging and incident archaeology agent-ergonomic and trustworthy.","acceptance_criteria":"Produce a self-contained contract for bounded as-of inspection and incident replay that downstream incidents, diagnostics, docs, examples, and validation work can implement directly.

The result must make it obvious what historical inspection is supported, how consumers request it, what guarantees or limits apply, and how missing or partial historical context is explained.","notes":"If an operator still has to hand-stitch raw event history just to understand what ntm believed around an incident boundary, this task is incomplete.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":180,"created_at":"2026-03-22T01:25:08.642590874Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-22T01:36:16.562470660Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["contracts","incidents","robot-redesign"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.13","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:25:08.642590874Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.13","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.10","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:25:55.502083327Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.13","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.14","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:36:16.561527894Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.13","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:25:58.728296447Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.13","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.7","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:25:57.951448289Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.13","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.8","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:25:57.150473214Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.13","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.9","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:25:56.295790944Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"bd-j9jo3.1.14","title":"robot-redesign/contracts: define sensitivity, redaction, and disclosure-control semantics","description":"Define how ntm robot surfaces classify sensitive material, redact it safely, and explain disclosure decisions so richer robot data never turns into accidental secret leakage.","design":"The contract should define a narrow, operator-facing disclosure model for robot mode rather than a generic privacy framework. It should cover pane output, mail snippets, command arguments, diagnostic evidence, replay snapshots, actuation outcomes, and any other robot-visible payloads that may contain secrets, personal data, internal addresses, or other material that should not be surfaced verbatim by default. It should specify stable machine-readable disclosure states such as visible, preview_only, redacted, withheld, or hashed; where safe previews are allowed; how redaction markers and reasons are represented; how rule version or policy provenance is surfaced; how allowlisted fields differ from normal text blobs; and how explainability, boundedness, history, replay, and transport parity interact with sensitivity handling. The goal is not to hide everything. The goal is to preserve agent ergonomics while ensuring richer robot payloads remain safe enough to expose and debug without leaking raw secrets.","acceptance_criteria":"Produce a self-contained contract for sensitivity classification, redaction markers, safe previews, disclosure-control states, and explanation semantics that downstream adapters, surfaces, replay, docs, and validation work can implement directly. The result must make it obvious when content is shown verbatim, summarized, hashed, previewed, redacted, or withheld; how a consumer can tell why that happened; and how those semantics remain stable across snapshot, digest, attention, inspect, replay, REST, and streaming views.","notes":"If richer robot outputs force future agents or operators to choose between usefulness and not leaking secrets, this task is incomplete.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":180,"created_at":"2026-03-22T01:34:08.686248205Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-22T01:36:15.722971404Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["contracts","robot-redesign","sensitivity"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.14","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:34:08.686248205Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.14","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:36:14.069722947Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.14","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.8","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:36:14.887882299Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.14","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.9","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:36:15.721875952Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
+{"id":"bd-j9jo3.1.15","title":"robot-redesign/contracts: define auditability, actor attribution, and operator-decision trail semantics","description":"Define how ntm records and exposes a trustworthy trail of operator and system decisions so later readers can tell who changed state, which request caused an effect, and why a disclosure or override happened.","design":"The contract should define a narrow operational audit model rather than a generic compliance subsystem. It should cover actor attribution for manual attention-state changes, actuation requests and outcomes, incident lifecycle changes, replay/export requests where relevant, and disclosure-control decisions that materially shape what a consumer can see. It should specify stable machine-readable audit-event shapes, actor identifiers or origin classes, request or outcome correlation fields, timestamps, reason or note fields, references to affected entities, and how auditability interacts with sensitivity redaction so the trail remains useful without leaking the underlying secret content. The contract should also define which events are durably retained versus summarized, how recent audit history appears in diagnostics or inspect flows, and how parity surfaces preserve the same semantics. The goal is not bureaucracy. The goal is operational trust: when a future agent or human asks who acknowledged this, who pinned it, who hid this evidence, or what request caused this change, ntm should have a first-class answer.","acceptance_criteria":"Produce a self-contained contract for audit events, actor attribution, decision-history references, and operator-trust semantics that downstream persistence, diagnostics, parity, docs, and validation work can implement directly. The result must make it obvious which state transitions are audit-worthy, how consumers correlate an audit record with the affected entity or request, how sensitivity rules constrain the trail, and how an operator discovers recent decision history without reading raw logs.","notes":"If future debugging still depends on vague guesswork about who changed operator state or why a disclosure decision happened, this task is incomplete.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":180,"created_at":"2026-03-22T01:56:56.301014492Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-22T01:57:44.726170078Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["audit","contracts","robot-redesign"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.15","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:56:56.301014492Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.15","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.10","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:57:43.822951975Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.15","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.11","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:57:44.724977453Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.15","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.8","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:57:42.075563452Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.15","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.9","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:57:42.945069124Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"bd-j9jo3.1.2","title":"robot-redesign/contracts: define the canonical projection section model","description":"Define the normalized section model that every major robot surface will share. This task turns vague ideas like sessions, work, coordination, quota, alerts, and incidents into explicit section boundaries and Go-struct-level concepts.","design":"The section model should answer: what top-level sections snapshot/status/attention/digest share, which fields are stable across transports, which data live inside session-level sections versus global sections, and which concepts deserve first-class sections rather than free-floating fields.\n\nThe goal is to make future renderers and APIs project from one section model rather than each inventing its own ad hoc composition rules.","acceptance_criteria":"Define a section map and normalized conceptual model covering at least summary, sessions, work, coordination, quota, alerts, incidents, attention, source_health, and next_actions, with enough detail to drive SQLite schema and output schemas downstream.","notes":"The section model should privilege operator comprehension over raw exhaustiveness. A concept becomes its own section only if it materially improves shared semantics across surfaces and transports.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":180,"created_at":"2026-03-21T23:34:17.956590019Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:34:32.681588370Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["contracts","projection","robot-redesign"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.2","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:34:17.956590019Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.2","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:34:32.680936349Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"bd-j9jo3.1.3","title":"robot-redesign/contracts: define schema identifiers, versioning rules, and checked-in artifacts","description":"Define how robot responses will advertise schema identity and evolution, and decide how checked-in JSON schema artifacts become part of the contract. This task exists to prevent drift between structs, capabilities, docs, and machine consumers.","design":"The contract should distinguish envelope version from payload schema identity, define naming such as ntm.robot.snapshot.v1, specify additive-versus-breaking changes and the version-bump rules they require, and describe how checked-in schema files, capabilities, and help output stay aligned.

This task should also explain why reflective schema generation alone is insufficient for long-lived contract stewardship.","acceptance_criteria":"Produce a self-contained schema/versioning policy that downstream registry and testing tasks can implement directly, including naming conventions, artifact layout expectations, and change-classification plus version-bump rules.","notes":"This task should bias toward explicit, boring contract discipline. Schema IDs are not marketing names; they are stability anchors for tooling and future maintainers.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":150,"created_at":"2026-03-21T23:34:18.770376450Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-22T00:01:39.923047171Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["contracts","robot-redesign","schema"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.3","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:34:18.770376450Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.3","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:34:33.091173527Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.3","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:34:33.504789471Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"bd-j9jo3.1.4","title":"robot-redesign/contracts: define freshness, degraded-state, and provenance semantics","description":"Define how robot surfaces describe data freshness, degraded sources, and provenance mode so agents can tell what is live, cached, partial, or unavailable. This task exists because the redesign only becomes trustworthy if consumers can reason about the quality of what they are seeing.","design":"The intended output is a section-level model for source_health, degraded_features, freshness_sec, collected_at, and provenance mode such as live, cached, or derived. The semantics should be strong enough that snapshot, status, digest, attention, and transport variants can all express partial failure without inventing bespoke warnings.\n\nThis task should explicitly reject noisy per-field provenance in favor of per-section and per-source reporting.","acceptance_criteria":"Produce a self-contained freshness/degraded-state contract that downstream SQLite, adapter, and surface tasks can implement directly.\n\nThe contract must specify where this metadata lives, how it behaves when sources fail, and how consumers should interpret it during the operator loop.","notes":"This is one of the major ideas worth stealing from vibe_cockpit, but adapted to ntm's tmux-first workflow rather than to periodic fleet collection.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":150,"created_at":"2026-03-21T23:34:19.628854190Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-21T23:34:34.330795735Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["contracts","freshness","robot-redesign"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.4","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:34:19.628854190Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.4","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:34:33.920854071Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.4","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:34:34.330062141Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
