 {"id":"bd-j9jo3.9.1","title":"robot-redesign/validation: add schema goldens and contract stability tests","description":"Add golden tests and contract stability checks for robot payload schemas, checked-in example payloads, and registry-backed discovery output. This task exists because the redesign only improves long-term quality if contract drift becomes obvious and explainable.","design":"The tests should pin checked-in schema artifacts, normative example payloads and scenario transcripts, registry-generated capabilities/help/schema views, representative payload shapes for core surfaces, canonical error or remediation examples for invalid cursor, resync-required, bounded-result, duplicate-request, and invalid-inspect conditions, request identity or idempotency examples, correlated actuation outcomes, operator-attention-state examples such as acknowledge or snooze or pin transitions, and diagnostic explainability examples such as explanation-handle shapes, evidence summaries, suppression markers, and why-this-is-stale or truncated flows. They should make breaking changes explicit, keep additive changes disciplined, and log schema IDs, example names, changed sections, error codes, request or outcome IDs, operator-state markers, diagnostic handles, and high-signal diffs when goldens move. The focus is not on testing every field serializer in isolation; it is on safeguarding the declared contract and its concrete examples.","acceptance_criteria":"This task is complete when schema, example, and discovery drift trigger obvious test failures with rich diagnostics, and maintainers can evolve the robot contract only through explicit intentional updates to schemas and examples, including retry-safe, attention-hygiene, and operator-override semantics.","notes":"Use the example corpus as an executable contract, not as a bag of arbitrary snapshots.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":180,"created_at":"2026-03-21T23:38:26.297471362Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-22T01:36:19.932723019Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["robot-redesign","schema","validation"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.10","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:23:35.335731985Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.11","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:29:52.264294078Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.12","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:48:01.309834452Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.13","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:26:01.211338268Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.14","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:36:19.931830708Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.5","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:48:15.728838931Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:57:25.868389436Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.7","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:02:38.566794194Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.9","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:17:54.239112622Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.6.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:40:14.153996914Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.6.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:40:14.668930347Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.6.3","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:40:15.315308706Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.6.4","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:40:15.839232826Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.6.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:48:16.937186344Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.6.7","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:10:37.649785822Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.7.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:40:13.617275560Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.9","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:38:26.297471362Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:48:16.306571964Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","title":"robot-redesign/validation: add benchmark and regression coverage for latency, payload size, and storage churn","description":"Add automated benchmark and regression coverage for the user-facing cost profile of the redesign. This task exists because robot mode ergonomics depend not only on semantic correctness but also on snapshot, status, digest, attention, inspect, and transport behavior staying fast, bounded, and operationally cheap as projects grow.","design":"The coverage should use the shared deterministic fixture corpus and Go testing infrastructure to measure snapshot, status, digest, attention, inspect, diagnostics, and renderer behavior under small, medium, and large scenarios plus repeated-event, retry-heavy, and operator-override-heavy scenarios. It should track payload bytes, section counts, raw event counts versus surfaced item counts where observable, truncation or pagination activation, latency, allocations, rows touched or rewritten where observable, replay throughput, diagnostic expansion cost, deduplication effectiveness, operator-state impact on surfaced queue size, and any storage-churn signals needed to verify SQLite stays operationally cheap. Use Go benchmarks and targeted regression tests rather than ad hoc shell loops. The logging should record scenario IDs, schema IDs, request IDs where relevant, render format, item counts, payload sizes, operator-state markers, suppression or resurfacing markers, diagnostic-surface depth where relevant, and enough supporting detail that a regression report explains what got slower or larger and why that matters to users.","acceptance_criteria":"This task is complete when the redesign has automated benchmark and regression coverage for latency, payload size, storage churn, compact-attention effectiveness, and operator-control overhead, with detailed logs that make regressions obvious and diagnosable. The result should prove that boundedness and performance budgets are being honored for representative scenarios rather than merely hoped for.","notes":"Fast, bounded outputs are part of the contract for agent-facing robot mode. Benchmark work should protect user experience and operational cost, not chase meaningless micro-optimizations.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":210,"created_at":"2026-03-21T23:55:45.991262114Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-22T01:37:28.896855399Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["benchmark","performance","robot-redesign","validation"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.11","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:29:57.571500782Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:57:28.813873196Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.2.4","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:57:29.449135271Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.3.5","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:36:39.832167367Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:23:48.140664593Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.7","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:30:09.314787309Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.8","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:48:12.943189537Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.5.4","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:26:11.351998992Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.6.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:57:30.103760616Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.6.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:57:30.760403187Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.6.3","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:57:31.431902328Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.6.4","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:57:32.090277353Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.6.5","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:57:32.790945414Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.6.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:57:33.501646942Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.6.7","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:10:40.688435708Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.8.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:57:34.326567098Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.8.3","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:57:35.045374334Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.9","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:55:45.991262114Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:57:35.744902360Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":341,"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","author":"ubuntu","text":"Watch-semantics follow-up: benchmark and regression coverage should measure idle-heartbeat overhead, filter selectivity costs, cadence adaptation under churn and degraded sources, and the operational cost difference between durable event publication and ephemeral keepalive traffic.","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:49:06Z"},{"id":345,"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","author":"ubuntu","text":"Historical-performance follow-up: benchmarks must measure replay and as-of latency, cache-hit versus reconstruction cost, payload-size behavior for historical responses, and SQLite churn introduced by replay caching so the feature stays operationally cheap enough for live debugging.","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:28:15Z"},{"id":361,"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.10","author":"ubuntu","text":"Sensitivity follow-up: benchmark coverage must measure redaction and safe-preview cost on hot surfaces and replay paths so the safety layer remains cheap enough for routine robot consumption.","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:37:28Z"}]}
 {"id":"bd-j9jo3.9.11","title":"robot-redesign/validation: add redaction, sensitivity, and disclosure-control verification coverage","description":"Add dedicated verification for sensitivity, redaction, and disclosure-control semantics so ntm can prove richer robot data stay safe across persistence, replay, diagnostics, and transport boundaries.","design":"The tests should cover contract examples for visible versus preview_only versus redacted versus withheld payloads; rule-version and reason markers; safe-preview generation for pane output, mail snippets, diagnostic evidence, and replay snapshots; no-leak guarantees in SQLite projections, attention journals, incident replay caches, REST payloads, and streaming events; allowlisted-field behavior; and explicit diagnostic explanations for why content was transformed. Coverage should include package-local unit tests, SQLite and restart integration tests, Go-based e2e scenarios, and benchmark or regression checks for redaction cost and payload-size effects. Logging should be excellent: scenario name, schema ID, rule version, disclosure state, hidden-field counts, hashed evidence handles, replay mode, and diffs that prove raw secrets were not emitted.","acceptance_criteria":"This task is complete when the redesign has explicit automated coverage proving that sensitive material is transformed or withheld consistently across live surfaces, replay, persistence, diagnostics, and parity transports, and when failures produce enough detailed logging that a maintainer can understand exactly what leaked, what was expected, and which rule or surface misbehaved.","notes":"Sensitivity handling is too important to leave as an implied side effect of generic tests. If a regression could leak a secret without a dedicated failing test and clear artifact trail, this task is incomplete.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":210,"created_at":"2026-03-22T01:34:08.838581790Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-22T01:36:46.226359266Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["robot-redesign","sensitivity","validation"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.11","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.14","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:36:40.673125135Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.11","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.5","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:36:41.531532027Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.11","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.3.5","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:36:42.403226219Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.11","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.5.4","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:36:43.306247021Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.11","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.6.7","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:36:44.270220056Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.11","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.8.3","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:36:45.281933126Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.11","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.9","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:34:08.838581790Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.11","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:36:46.225757018Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
+{"id":"bd-j9jo3.9.12","title":"robot-redesign/validation: add audit-trail and actor-attribution verification coverage","description":"Add dedicated verification for auditability and actor attribution so the redesign can prove operator-state changes, actuation loops, incident transitions, and disclosure decisions remain traceable across restart, replay, and transport boundaries.","design":"The tests should cover contract examples for actor-attributed attention-state changes, actuation request and outcome trails, incident lifecycle history, audit visibility in diagnostics or inspect flows, and the interaction between sensitivity redaction and audit usefulness. Coverage should include package-local unit tests for store APIs and event shaping, SQLite or restart integration tests for retention and replay behavior, Go-based e2e scenarios where multiple actors or sessions mutate state, and benchmark or regression checks that audit capture does not make hot paths noisy or expensive. Logging should be excellent: actor identifiers, origin classes, request IDs, affected references, timestamps, decision reasons, disclosure states, replay mode, and diffs that explain missing or malformed audit history.","acceptance_criteria":"This task is complete when automated coverage proves that audit-worthy events are persisted and exposed consistently enough that a maintainer can answer who changed this, what request caused this effect, and why this disclosure or override happened, with detailed logs when any part of that trail breaks.","notes":"Auditability is a product feature here, not compliance theater. If a failure can erase or obscure operator trust history without a focused failing test, this task is incomplete.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":210,"created_at":"2026-03-22T01:56:56.309450111Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-22T01:57:22.538806002Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["audit","robot-redesign","validation"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.9.12","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.9","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:56:56.309450111Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"bd-j9jo3.9.2","title":"robot-redesign/validation: add SQLite, adapter, degraded-source, and restart-recovery integration tests","description":"Add integration coverage for the runtime projection store, adapter normalization, degraded-source handling, attention replay, watermark persistence, incident evolution, and restart recovery behavior. This task exists because the hardest parts of the redesign live at the seams between subsystems, not inside isolated helper functions.","design":"The tests should exercise realistic sequences such as source outage followed by partial recovery, ntm restart followed by resumed delta computation, incident promotion after repeated evidence, projection rebuild with durable cursor continuity, ambiguous timeout followed by safe retry, duplicate request suppression with later verified outcome, repeated flapping source with cooldown and resurfacing, acknowledgment followed by material change and resurfacing, snooze expiry, pin and manual escalation behavior, retention or pruning decisions, and partial transport resync. They should use the shared deterministic harness and log scenario IDs, request IDs, idempotency keys, cursor transitions, watermark state, source_health changes, operator-state transitions, suppression or resurfacing markers, incident fingerprints, and assertion diffs with enough detail to diagnose failures quickly. This task should prove the redesign works as an operational system, not just as a collection of structs.","acceptance_criteria":"This task is complete when the critical persistence, degradation, replay, restart-safety, retry-safety, attention-hygiene, and operator-control promises of the redesign are pinned by deterministic integration tests that emit rich debugging context and fail loudly when those promises regress.","notes":"Future self: if you ever want to simplify something 'just for now,' make sure these tests still express the product promises that matter.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type